Flight from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke away from their communist past; others were less successful, and a few catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category until recently.
Their economic and political failure was largely due to – actively supported by Russia – secessionist movements that attempted to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts broke out in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence in these areas into "peacekeeping troops" to maintain control.
For a long time, there was concern that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly escalate into hot wars.
Not only did this not happen, but we can now speak of solutions – because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve a breakthrough towards a market economy and democracy.
The European Union's "neighborhood policy" has also contributed to these developments.
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Already perilously close to a failed state, Georgia has since turned to the West.
The success of various "color revolutions" in former Soviet block countries also triggered change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms, the goal of which is to draw closer to the EU.
These changes have sparked new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries through peaceful means.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with enormous economic problems, making it unsuitable for investment.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and wood, but its economy grew.
In northeastern Estonia with its predominantly Russian-speaking population, who had settled here during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called "autonomy movement".
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and disrupted gas supplies.
High tariffs were levied on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its cool.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to reorient its economy towards the West.
Western Europe, on the other hand, did what it could to integrate the Baltic states – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time attempted to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and thus Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries and joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported by Western Europe to the same extent.
However, Georgia appeared less attractive as a partner than the Baltic states; the 1990s were characterized by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, in which two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – effectively seceded with Russian support.
The country has done its best to forget its sorrowful past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army has been strengthened, and the country's leadership is young, dynamic, and enthusiastically striving to move the country forward.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is striving to defuse tensions over Abkhazia and South Ossetia; however, Russia accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
Its main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to block reconciliation with the rebellious regions.
The powers at play in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also important.
Estonia has shown that it can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support, both at its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe allowed Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has a legitimate reason to hope that it will achieve true independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than Estonia or even Georgia ever were?
The lack of reform progress is partly the result of the secessionist movements supported by Russia.
That the industrialized region of Transnistria, whose population, which speaks Russian and Ukrainian, feared closer ties with Romania, as the majority of Moldovans are of Romanian descent, would secede from Moldova, dealt a severe blow to the country's independence from the very beginning.
A civil war followed, and in 1992, Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they remain to this day.
The independence of Transnistria has never been recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there is lawlessness and corruption there.
Moldova is heavily indebted, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally shuts down gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Moldovan government representatives have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to try to find a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has asked the EU observer mission Eubam for help, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks current insights into the situation in Moldova.
In April, for example, the EU and the US only learned about a proposed peace agreement through a leaked report in Germany.
This, it seems, would favor Russia, as Moldova is supposed to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity in it.
If Russia has outmaneuvered the West in this way, it would be a perilous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
